WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.736
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:00:05.902 --> 00:00:07.610
BRIAN KELLY: I've
always been a nerd when

00:00:07.610 --> 00:00:08.777
it came to miles and points.

00:00:08.777 --> 00:00:10.910
Like in the '90s, my
dad was a consultant,

00:00:10.910 --> 00:00:13.850
and I basically helped manage
his travel and his points.

00:00:13.850 --> 00:00:15.522
And I was 12 when
I first realized--

00:00:15.522 --> 00:00:17.480
I said, we have all these
frequent flyer miles.

00:00:17.480 --> 00:00:19.290
And he's like, well, if you
can figure out how to use them,

00:00:19.290 --> 00:00:20.390
we'll go on vacation.

00:00:20.390 --> 00:00:23.330
And he's like, let's go to
Orlando or somewhere basic.

00:00:23.330 --> 00:00:25.993
And sassy old
12-year-old me was like--

00:00:25.993 --> 00:00:28.160
I had just read the book
"The Firm" by John Grisham,

00:00:28.160 --> 00:00:29.330
and they went to
the Cayman Islands.

00:00:29.330 --> 00:00:31.620
And I would just remember--
this sounds amazing!

00:00:31.620 --> 00:00:34.160
So I called up US Airways
and talked to Peggy

00:00:34.160 --> 00:00:35.330
and became her best friend.

00:00:35.330 --> 00:00:38.900
And somehow our family of
six went on a free trip

00:00:38.900 --> 00:00:39.980
to the Cayman Islands.

00:00:39.980 --> 00:00:43.310
And so that's when I really--
that was in the '90s.

00:00:43.310 --> 00:00:45.080
And then fast forward to '07.

00:00:45.080 --> 00:00:46.340
I get a job at Morgan Stanley.

00:00:46.340 --> 00:00:49.820
My job was actually to
recruit computer scientists

00:00:49.820 --> 00:00:53.210
and engineers, and my main
job was to convince MIT grads

00:00:53.210 --> 00:00:55.040
and Cornell grads to
not work at Google

00:00:55.040 --> 00:00:57.620
and instead work in
finance, which, as you guys

00:00:57.620 --> 00:00:59.540
can imagine-- are there
many technologists

00:00:59.540 --> 00:01:02.810
here, like real nerds?

00:01:02.810 --> 00:01:03.780
OK, good.

00:01:03.780 --> 00:01:06.370
In any case, my job was to
convince computer scientists

00:01:06.370 --> 00:01:07.910
to not work at Google.

00:01:07.910 --> 00:01:09.410
So they gave me
a corporate Amex.

00:01:09.410 --> 00:01:11.930
And I was spending like crazy,
putting all the career fairs,

00:01:11.930 --> 00:01:15.530
and then taking
people out to dinners.

00:01:15.530 --> 00:01:17.870
I was 27 years old but
spending over $1 million a year

00:01:17.870 --> 00:01:21.440
on a corporate Amex that
Morgan Stanley paid directly.

00:01:21.440 --> 00:01:24.080
And as long as you paid
I think it was $49,

00:01:24.080 --> 00:01:25.340
you could get all the points.

00:01:25.340 --> 00:01:27.410
Most of my co-workers
didn't even know that.

00:01:27.410 --> 00:01:29.760
And then everyone hated the
expense system at that time.

00:01:29.760 --> 00:01:31.260
You actually had
to fax in receipts.

00:01:31.260 --> 00:01:33.050
And it was a whole process.

00:01:33.050 --> 00:01:34.550
So they didn't
understand that I was

00:01:34.550 --> 00:01:38.140
like banking tons of points,
and I made it out to be like,

00:01:38.140 --> 00:01:40.900
guys, I'll take
one for the team.

00:01:40.900 --> 00:01:41.810
I'll do the expenses.

00:01:41.810 --> 00:01:45.110
And everyone was like,
thank you so much!

00:01:45.110 --> 00:01:46.700
So I really got into points.

00:01:46.700 --> 00:01:49.700
And I was traveling
first class on weekends.

00:01:49.700 --> 00:01:51.380
And all my friends
would always-- like,

00:01:51.380 --> 00:01:53.540
my co-workers thought I
was a trust fund baby.

00:01:53.540 --> 00:01:54.860
And it was all the points.

00:01:54.860 --> 00:01:58.070
And so finally I shared
my tips, and I would

00:01:58.070 --> 00:02:00.550
have a queue around my cubicle.

00:02:00.550 --> 00:02:03.050
And people would just-- even
my managing directors at Morgan

00:02:03.050 --> 00:02:04.280
Stanley were like--

00:02:04.280 --> 00:02:06.140
they would come up to me like,
I just spent a million points.

00:02:06.140 --> 00:02:07.130
I'm buying a grill.

00:02:07.130 --> 00:02:09.210
And I would like smack them.

00:02:09.210 --> 00:02:11.390
So I really enjoyed
whipping people into shape.

00:02:16.330 --> 00:02:18.620
I almost became a teacher
after college for Teach

00:02:18.620 --> 00:02:20.060
for America, if anyone's
familiar with that.

00:02:20.060 --> 00:02:21.143
So I like teaching people.

00:02:21.143 --> 00:02:23.250
I love travel, and I just
love beating the system.

00:02:23.250 --> 00:02:24.470
So that was my background.

00:02:24.470 --> 00:02:26.810
So as I look now-- so
I started the blog,

00:02:26.810 --> 00:02:28.770
just like never in
a million years.

00:02:28.770 --> 00:02:30.020
It was never about monetizing.

00:02:30.020 --> 00:02:32.648
I didn't even do Google AdSense.

00:02:32.648 --> 00:02:34.940
People were like, just put
Google AdSense on your blog.

00:02:34.940 --> 00:02:36.590
You'll make $10 a month.

00:02:36.590 --> 00:02:37.890
It's better than nothing.

00:02:37.890 --> 00:02:39.210
And I remember being like, no.

00:02:39.210 --> 00:02:41.420
This is my passion and joy.

00:02:41.420 --> 00:02:44.990
And I'm not here to make
money off of content.

00:02:44.990 --> 00:02:46.575
And everyone's like, you moron.

00:02:46.575 --> 00:02:47.950
That's the point
of the internet.

00:02:47.950 --> 00:02:49.658
And I remember someone
saying, you really

00:02:49.658 --> 00:02:51.950
think Google wants to serve
you search results just out

00:02:51.950 --> 00:02:52.543
of niceness?

00:02:52.543 --> 00:02:53.960
Like, no, they're
making bank too.

00:02:53.960 --> 00:02:54.860
It's OK.

00:02:54.860 --> 00:02:57.770
You can help people
and make money.

00:02:57.770 --> 00:02:59.240
It's not like they're at odds.

00:02:59.240 --> 00:03:00.440
LESLIE TOBIN: Absolutely.

00:03:00.440 --> 00:03:01.482
BRIAN KELLY: In any case.

00:03:01.482 --> 00:03:03.842
So I started blogging, and
I had no idea what SEO was.

00:03:03.842 --> 00:03:05.550
But my friend gave me
really good advice.

00:03:05.550 --> 00:03:09.050
And he was like, just do good
content every day, if you can,

00:03:09.050 --> 00:03:11.420
and if people like it.

00:03:11.420 --> 00:03:14.030
So I enjoyed every friend I had.

00:03:14.030 --> 00:03:15.830
I posted myself to Facebook.

00:03:15.830 --> 00:03:18.240
I was on forums,
linking to my blog.

00:03:18.240 --> 00:03:21.700
And slowly but surely,
people started to like it.

00:03:21.700 --> 00:03:23.450
And every time I do
see a Google employee,

00:03:23.450 --> 00:03:24.470
I try to give them hugs.

00:03:24.470 --> 00:03:26.610
Because, I mean,
even to this day,

00:03:26.610 --> 00:03:29.660
last year we hit 4 and 1/2
million monthly uniques.

00:03:29.660 --> 00:03:31.270
In March we just hit 10 million.

00:03:31.270 --> 00:03:35.540
And like almost 50% of
that comes from Google.

00:03:35.540 --> 00:03:36.510
So thank you.

00:03:36.510 --> 00:03:39.140
Thank you, Google,
for making me rich.

00:03:39.140 --> 00:03:40.732
[LAUGHTER]

00:03:40.732 --> 00:03:41.940
LESLIE TOBIN: You're welcome.

00:03:41.940 --> 00:03:43.760
BRIAN KELLY: So
anyway, I don't know.

00:03:43.760 --> 00:03:46.190
So I started as a blog, and
it really just took off.

00:03:46.190 --> 00:03:49.318
And I made the decision about
nine months in to quit my job.

00:03:49.318 --> 00:03:51.860
But I really got lucky, because
the credit card companies had

00:03:51.860 --> 00:03:53.943
approached me and were
like, you know our products

00:03:53.943 --> 00:03:54.800
better than we do.

00:03:54.800 --> 00:03:57.800
And it was at the same time,
coming out of the recession,

00:03:57.800 --> 00:04:00.290
and they wanted the millennial
audience that I naturally

00:04:00.290 --> 00:04:01.603
had an ability to speak to.

00:04:01.603 --> 00:04:03.770
And also I could market
their products in a way they

00:04:03.770 --> 00:04:04.270
couldn't.

00:04:04.270 --> 00:04:06.735
Like, Chase can't take out a
full-page "New York Times" ad

00:04:06.735 --> 00:04:09.110
and tell you that the best
way to use the British Airways

00:04:09.110 --> 00:04:12.410
card is to fly American
Airlines or [INAUDIBLE]..

00:04:12.410 --> 00:04:13.378
There's a lot of--

00:04:13.378 --> 00:04:15.170
so I was a blogger, an
independent blogger,

00:04:15.170 --> 00:04:16.928
who could break it
down right away.

00:04:16.928 --> 00:04:17.845
It was very effective.

00:04:17.845 --> 00:04:19.015
LESLIE TOBIN: Absolutely.

00:04:19.015 --> 00:04:22.560
BRIAN KELLY: Once I started
making money doing that,

00:04:22.560 --> 00:04:23.390
it just took off.

00:04:23.390 --> 00:04:25.730
And now we just launched
in the UK on Thursday.

00:04:25.730 --> 00:04:26.420
LESLIE TOBIN: Very exciting.

00:04:26.420 --> 00:04:27.322
BRIAN KELLY: We
can clap for that.

00:04:27.322 --> 00:04:28.072
LESLIE TOBIN: Yay!

00:04:28.072 --> 00:04:31.610
[APPLAUSE]

00:04:31.610 --> 00:04:34.480
So Nicky, you joined The Points
Guy team much more recently.

00:04:34.480 --> 00:04:35.230
NICKY KELVIN: Yes.

00:04:35.230 --> 00:04:37.063
LESLIE TOBIN: But I
understand that you have

00:04:37.063 --> 00:04:38.370
been a longtime points guru.

00:04:38.370 --> 00:04:40.410
Tell me a little bit
about your journey.

00:04:40.410 --> 00:04:42.253
NICKY KELVIN: So, like
Brian, my beginnings

00:04:42.253 --> 00:04:44.670
was something completely-- our
professional beginnings was

00:04:44.670 --> 00:04:45.962
something completely different.

00:04:45.962 --> 00:04:48.750
So I started out on a
path being a lawyer,

00:04:48.750 --> 00:04:52.640
trained as a
solicitor in the city,

00:04:52.640 --> 00:04:57.950
in this big, corporate,
scary American law firm,

00:04:57.950 --> 00:04:59.950
then made a jump from
there into a record label.

00:04:59.950 --> 00:05:01.325
So for five years,
I was a lawyer

00:05:01.325 --> 00:05:05.280
for a record label, Virgin
AMI, which was very different,

00:05:05.280 --> 00:05:07.590
but I was still a lawyer.

00:05:07.590 --> 00:05:10.050
Alongside all of this stuff,
I was also a photographer

00:05:10.050 --> 00:05:12.980
and got very lucky to
shoot loads of big artists.

00:05:12.980 --> 00:05:16.500
And really what I loved taking
pictures of was airplanes

00:05:16.500 --> 00:05:19.470
and me on airplanes,
and aviation

00:05:19.470 --> 00:05:23.350
was my biggest passion, always,
since I was a little kid.

00:05:23.350 --> 00:05:27.268
And so I was very lucky to have
a sister who was cabin crew.

00:05:27.268 --> 00:05:28.560
She worked for British Airways.

00:05:28.560 --> 00:05:32.880
And so I spent my teenage years
and going to student years--

00:05:32.880 --> 00:05:35.370
like the time when it was
perfect for me to do it--

00:05:35.370 --> 00:05:38.280
flying around the world on
the cheap, 90% discount,

00:05:38.280 --> 00:05:40.445
staying in the best hotels,
flying with my sister

00:05:40.445 --> 00:05:42.570
where I'd get on the plane
and she would just say--

00:05:42.570 --> 00:05:45.000
you know, I'd have an
economy standby ticket.

00:05:45.000 --> 00:05:46.667
And she'd be like,
just sit there.

00:05:46.667 --> 00:05:48.750
And you know, I'd be in
business class every time.

00:05:48.750 --> 00:05:49.500
BRIAN KELLY: Nepotism.

00:05:49.500 --> 00:05:50.417
NICKY KELVIN: It was--

00:05:50.417 --> 00:05:52.500
yeah, yeah.

00:05:52.500 --> 00:05:57.030
And then she ruined my life
by getting married and having

00:05:57.030 --> 00:05:58.090
children.

00:05:58.090 --> 00:05:59.820
[LAUGHTER]

00:06:03.570 --> 00:06:06.070
Actually, I was telling
this story at the weekend,

00:06:06.070 --> 00:06:08.460
and she said that
ruined her life too.

00:06:08.460 --> 00:06:09.798
[LAUGHTER]

00:06:09.798 --> 00:06:12.090
BRIAN KELLY: Nothing against
having kids, we love kids.

00:06:12.090 --> 00:06:12.900
NICKY KELVIN: She
was in the room--

00:06:12.900 --> 00:06:14.850
BRIAN KELLY: We have a
whole family section.

00:06:14.850 --> 00:06:16.800
NICKY KELVIN: So I had
to find another way

00:06:16.800 --> 00:06:19.770
because her husband and kids
were then on her concessions.

00:06:19.770 --> 00:06:22.350
And I found miles
and points as the way

00:06:22.350 --> 00:06:26.580
to be able to still travel
nicely and get deals.

00:06:26.580 --> 00:06:29.910
And I guess I always just
wanted to learn loopholes

00:06:29.910 --> 00:06:31.470
or like just learn
these programs.

00:06:31.470 --> 00:06:35.220
It was kind of the geeky side
of me really appreciated that.

00:06:35.220 --> 00:06:38.550
And so that was maybe 10 years
ago that I got into this game

00:06:38.550 --> 00:06:40.290
and realized there
was a real benefit

00:06:40.290 --> 00:06:43.792
to be had even out of the UK and
started earning miles however

00:06:43.792 --> 00:06:46.000
way I could and then started
to tell people about it.

00:06:46.000 --> 00:06:47.850
So I was doing all this
stuff and people were like,

00:06:47.850 --> 00:06:48.725
how are you doing it?

00:06:48.725 --> 00:06:51.640
And I'm naturally
like a sharer and want

00:06:51.640 --> 00:06:52.880
to tell people about stuff.

00:06:52.880 --> 00:06:55.230
BRIAN KELLY: You follow him
on Instagram, an oversharer

00:06:55.230 --> 00:06:57.132
sometimes.

00:06:57.132 --> 00:06:58.590
NICKY KELVIN: No--
OK, yeah, maybe.

00:06:58.590 --> 00:06:59.880
[LAUGHTER]

00:06:59.880 --> 00:07:02.265
Like when the stories
are like dots at the top.

00:07:02.265 --> 00:07:04.320
BRIAN KELLY: Time
to go to bed, Nicky.

00:07:04.320 --> 00:07:07.650
NICKY KELVIN: So I start
to tell people about it,

00:07:07.650 --> 00:07:11.820
started sort of writing a blog,
and just sharing information,

00:07:11.820 --> 00:07:14.070
and helping people I knew--
my friends, my family,

00:07:14.070 --> 00:07:15.470
to just to get into--

00:07:15.470 --> 00:07:17.465
BRIAN KELLY: He literally
is copying my story.

00:07:17.465 --> 00:07:18.830
NICKY KELVIN: [LAUGHS] Yeah.

00:07:18.830 --> 00:07:19.330
Yeah.

00:07:21.840 --> 00:07:23.970
And then Brian
and I, who'd known

00:07:23.970 --> 00:07:26.580
each other for a number of
years from social media,

00:07:26.580 --> 00:07:29.465
when the UK thing for
TPG was happening,

00:07:29.465 --> 00:07:30.840
Brian and I talked
about it maybe

00:07:30.840 --> 00:07:33.173
three or four years-- three
years ago I was in New York.

00:07:33.173 --> 00:07:35.070
And he said, I'd love
to come to London.

00:07:35.070 --> 00:07:37.680
The UK is the second biggest
readership of The Points Guy.

00:07:37.680 --> 00:07:40.288
So of the 10 million monthly
uniques, about 300,000

00:07:40.288 --> 00:07:41.580
per month were based in the UK.

00:07:41.580 --> 00:07:43.050
So we knew there
were people here,

00:07:43.050 --> 00:07:45.570
but we weren't serving
them any UK content.

00:07:45.570 --> 00:07:49.205
So my journey, then,
suddenly was faced--

00:07:49.205 --> 00:07:50.580
my professional
journey was faced

00:07:50.580 --> 00:07:52.290
with this whole new opportunity.

00:07:52.290 --> 00:07:55.620
And being a
photographer and lawyer

00:07:55.620 --> 00:07:58.680
was then very
quickly transformed

00:07:58.680 --> 00:08:00.960
into joining The Points
Guy last November

00:08:00.960 --> 00:08:03.720
to really follow my passion and
bring all my different skills

00:08:03.720 --> 00:08:05.743
together in one new job.

00:08:05.743 --> 00:08:06.660
LESLIE TOBIN: Amazing.

00:08:06.660 --> 00:08:07.780
Very cool.

00:08:07.780 --> 00:08:09.300
And so when was it
that you realized

00:08:09.300 --> 00:08:10.890
that this was more
than just a hobby

00:08:10.890 --> 00:08:12.870
and that you really wanted
to focus full time on this?

00:08:12.870 --> 00:08:13.920
BRIAN KELLY: Yeah,
well, the first time

00:08:13.920 --> 00:08:14.910
I realized this was--

00:08:14.910 --> 00:08:17.910
the weirdest moment-- so
I started June of 2010.

00:08:17.910 --> 00:08:20.190
And I was at a cocktail party
in New York in November,

00:08:20.190 --> 00:08:21.690
and I had just
shared this deal that

00:08:21.690 --> 00:08:24.840
went somewhat viral, this
crazy deal where you could

00:08:24.840 --> 00:08:27.190
go to Las Vegas for like $12.

00:08:27.190 --> 00:08:31.640
And I basically-- it was from
the bowels of the internet.

00:08:31.640 --> 00:08:33.580
There were-- before Reddit--

00:08:33.580 --> 00:08:34.973
all these weird subgroups.

00:08:34.973 --> 00:08:37.390
And basically I was able to
translate these complex deals,

00:08:37.390 --> 00:08:38.490
and it went viral.

00:08:38.490 --> 00:08:39.750
And I remember being
at a cocktail party,

00:08:39.750 --> 00:08:40.833
and someone's eyes lit up.

00:08:40.833 --> 00:08:42.780
And they're like,
you're The Points Guy?

00:08:42.780 --> 00:08:45.180
Which never happened.

00:08:45.180 --> 00:08:48.810
I was still an HR associate
at Morgan Stanley.

00:08:48.810 --> 00:08:49.620
And I was blogging.

00:08:49.620 --> 00:08:52.037
And then I was like,
this is a freaking brand.

00:08:52.037 --> 00:08:53.370
I didn't realize it was a brand.

00:08:53.370 --> 00:08:55.593
And my mom, soon
thereafter, texted

00:08:55.593 --> 00:08:57.510
TPG, when are you coming
home for the weekend?

00:08:57.510 --> 00:08:58.890
I'm like, what?

00:08:58.890 --> 00:09:00.030
It's so weird.

00:09:00.030 --> 00:09:03.360
Like, my mom is calling me an
acronym of a blog I started it.

00:09:05.910 --> 00:09:07.767
I mean, I wish I could
say I was super brave

00:09:07.767 --> 00:09:09.600
and just knew it was
going to be successful.

00:09:09.600 --> 00:09:13.590
But I got really lucky with--

00:09:13.590 --> 00:09:15.370
April of 2011, the
power of press.

00:09:15.370 --> 00:09:17.370
So "The New York Times"
had actually emailed me.

00:09:17.370 --> 00:09:20.340
It went into my spam,
thepointsguy@gmail spam box

00:09:20.340 --> 00:09:20.970
for two months.

00:09:20.970 --> 00:09:23.428
And for some reason, I was
bored and going through my spam,

00:09:23.428 --> 00:09:24.600
and I realized, oh my god.

00:09:24.600 --> 00:09:26.910
"The New York Times," Seth
Kugel, had emailed me.

00:09:26.910 --> 00:09:28.743
And he's like, I hear
you're The Points Guy.

00:09:28.743 --> 00:09:30.160
But for The Frugal
Traveler, which

00:09:30.160 --> 00:09:32.285
was his column in "The New
York Times" at the time,

00:09:32.285 --> 00:09:34.520
he goes, frugal budget
travelers don't need points.

00:09:34.520 --> 00:09:35.960
Just get the
cheapest ticket ever.

00:09:35.960 --> 00:09:37.820
That's what I'm going
to buy, all of my--

00:09:37.820 --> 00:09:39.888
I was like, are you kidding me?

00:09:39.888 --> 00:09:41.430
I was like, that's
the dumbest thing.

00:09:41.430 --> 00:09:43.330
Budget travelers of
course need points.

00:09:43.330 --> 00:09:45.830
And oh, by the way, you can buy
cheap flights and do points.

00:09:45.830 --> 00:09:47.565
You can walk and chew gum.

00:09:47.565 --> 00:09:48.440
But I was so annoyed.

00:09:48.440 --> 00:09:50.148
Because in the press,
it was always like,

00:09:50.148 --> 00:09:51.080
points are useless.

00:09:51.080 --> 00:09:52.850
You can never use them.

00:09:52.850 --> 00:09:55.370
And that's what all the
kind of old school travel--

00:09:55.370 --> 00:09:56.360
So anyway.

00:09:56.360 --> 00:09:57.980
I was in "The New
York Times" on a day

00:09:57.980 --> 00:10:00.313
that there was this British
Airways 100,000 point offer.

00:10:00.313 --> 00:10:01.550
It was April of 2011.

00:10:01.550 --> 00:10:04.250
At the time, I was making
a couple thousand a month.

00:10:06.885 --> 00:10:08.510
I mean, it's all
about luck and timing.

00:10:08.510 --> 00:10:10.135
But "The New York
Times" piece came out

00:10:10.135 --> 00:10:11.540
on the day this
British Airways--

00:10:11.540 --> 00:10:14.200
and I was getting paid $150
per approval from Chase.

00:10:14.200 --> 00:10:16.200
So on a normal day, I'd
have like maybe a couple

00:10:16.200 --> 00:10:18.350
of people getting.

00:10:18.350 --> 00:10:21.950
But like 1,000 people signed
up for the card that day.

00:10:21.950 --> 00:10:24.210
So I made 150 grand in one day--

00:10:24.210 --> 00:10:25.447
LESLIE TOBIN: Wow.

00:10:25.447 --> 00:10:27.530
BRIAN KELLY: --through the
power of viral content.

00:10:27.530 --> 00:10:28.925
I was doing Facebook
at the time,

00:10:28.925 --> 00:10:30.050
but people started sharing.

00:10:30.050 --> 00:10:32.220
And I remember people were
emailing me, thank you.

00:10:32.220 --> 00:10:34.990
My family of 10
just got this card--

00:10:34.990 --> 00:10:36.730
and you could use
it at the time for--

00:10:36.730 --> 00:10:38.795
it was 20 round trip
flights to Miami,

00:10:38.795 --> 00:10:40.170
or you could go
to Easter Island.

00:10:40.170 --> 00:10:41.720
BA's old program was unreal.

00:10:41.720 --> 00:10:43.930
You could stop unlimited
amount of times.

00:10:43.930 --> 00:10:44.680
LESLIE TOBIN: Wow.

00:10:44.680 --> 00:10:45.140
BRIAN KELLY: And
I just remember.

00:10:45.140 --> 00:10:47.223
This is a business, because
people are thanking me

00:10:47.223 --> 00:10:48.470
for making me $1,000.

00:10:48.470 --> 00:10:49.680
That's pretty cool.

00:10:49.680 --> 00:10:50.860
[LAUGHTER]

00:10:50.860 --> 00:10:53.180
So I was on paper making
a good amount of money

00:10:53.180 --> 00:10:57.080
when I quit the job, although
it sort of was a gold rush were

00:10:57.080 --> 00:11:00.050
all these bloggers-- it became
the wild wild west of blogging,

00:11:00.050 --> 00:11:02.658
where everyone could become
a credit card affiliate.

00:11:02.658 --> 00:11:04.700
And coming from finance,
I knew that that was not

00:11:04.700 --> 00:11:05.283
going to last.

00:11:05.283 --> 00:11:07.652
And you have to
invest in compliance

00:11:07.652 --> 00:11:09.110
and making sure
you're buttoned up.

00:11:09.110 --> 00:11:12.052
And you can tell people
to cancel on open cards

00:11:12.052 --> 00:11:14.510
because that makes you money
right then and there, but then

00:11:14.510 --> 00:11:15.927
of course lawyers at banks.

00:11:15.927 --> 00:11:17.510
So I think that's
why I've been able--

00:11:17.510 --> 00:11:20.132
The Points Guy, there's 100
other points blogs in the US,

00:11:20.132 --> 00:11:21.590
but we've always
had a very-- like,

00:11:21.590 --> 00:11:22.673
we work with our partners.

00:11:22.673 --> 00:11:26.397
We see long term, like
the real gray area

00:11:26.397 --> 00:11:27.480
stuff we don't talk about.

00:11:27.480 --> 00:11:29.360
And that's good anyway, because
everyone in the industry

00:11:29.360 --> 00:11:30.080
reads our site.

00:11:30.080 --> 00:11:32.450
So there are weird ways
to earn miles and points

00:11:32.450 --> 00:11:34.617
that are borderline
unethical that you can do,

00:11:34.617 --> 00:11:36.200
but that's not what
The Points Guy is,

00:11:36.200 --> 00:11:38.010
and that's why we've
been able to grow it.

00:11:38.010 --> 00:11:38.960
LESLIE TOBIN: Absolutely.

00:11:38.960 --> 00:11:40.310
BRIAN KELLY: But yes, I got
lucky I was making money

00:11:40.310 --> 00:11:40.850
when I quit.

00:11:40.850 --> 00:11:44.090
But my mom still was
like, how are you going

00:11:44.090 --> 00:11:46.230
to pay for health benefits?

00:11:46.230 --> 00:11:46.820
I'm rich.

00:11:46.820 --> 00:11:48.640
I'll be able to pay for them--

00:11:48.640 --> 00:11:49.270
allegedly.

00:11:49.270 --> 00:11:51.290
They still had to loan
me $10,000 from when

00:11:51.290 --> 00:11:53.210
I quit because I still
hadn't been paid.

00:11:53.210 --> 00:11:55.670
But luckily the check
came in the mail.

00:11:55.670 --> 00:11:56.610
LESLIE TOBIN: Yes.

00:11:56.610 --> 00:11:57.250
Amazing.

00:11:57.250 --> 00:12:00.320
So do you actually engage
with credit card companies

00:12:00.320 --> 00:12:04.250
and advise them on
loyalty programs and point

00:12:04.250 --> 00:12:06.458
schemes or other propositions
that they're launching?

00:12:06.458 --> 00:12:07.208
BRIAN KELLY: Yeah.

00:12:07.208 --> 00:12:08.350
I mean, in the US, we do.

00:12:08.350 --> 00:12:09.830
We're even doing
it here in the UK.

00:12:09.830 --> 00:12:11.480
The UK needs a
little bit of help.

00:12:11.480 --> 00:12:14.830
Our goal here is to build up and
get people engaged in points.

00:12:14.830 --> 00:12:17.255
In the US, we launch
every major credit card.

00:12:17.255 --> 00:12:19.880
The Chase Sapphire Reserve was
a turning point in our business.

00:12:19.880 --> 00:12:22.400
I mean, we knew about that
product for four months

00:12:22.400 --> 00:12:23.900
before we pitched
them the business.

00:12:23.900 --> 00:12:26.450
And Chase made a bet to launch
it with The Points Guys.

00:12:26.450 --> 00:12:28.530
So there were no
ads, no commercials.

00:12:28.530 --> 00:12:31.070
We were the exclusive
launch partner.

00:12:31.070 --> 00:12:32.870
And Chase announced
the Sapphire Reserve.

00:12:32.870 --> 00:12:35.160
I get chills thinking about it.

00:12:35.160 --> 00:12:35.840
It's true.

00:12:35.840 --> 00:12:38.420
It's coming, and the
Points Guy has the details.

00:12:38.420 --> 00:12:39.320
And it was our post.

00:12:39.320 --> 00:12:41.930
Because we respected the
embargo as it started to leak.

00:12:41.930 --> 00:12:44.270
So as a partner and
thinking long term,

00:12:44.270 --> 00:12:45.560
so they actually gave us--

00:12:45.560 --> 00:12:47.060
think about it, the
best credit card

00:12:47.060 --> 00:12:48.890
to ever hit the
market they announced

00:12:48.890 --> 00:12:51.010
on social media with a
link to The Points Guy.

00:12:51.010 --> 00:12:51.760
LESLIE TOBIN: Wow.

00:12:51.760 --> 00:12:55.175
BRIAN KELLY: This multi-billion
dollar public company,

00:12:55.175 --> 00:12:56.800
but they partnered
with us in that way,

00:12:56.800 --> 00:12:59.205
and then it went viral.

00:12:59.205 --> 00:13:00.830
LESLIE TOBIN: Can
you talk a little bit

00:13:00.830 --> 00:13:03.130
about what the Chase
Sapphire Reserve card is?

00:13:03.130 --> 00:13:03.410
BRIAN KELLY: Oh, yeah.

00:13:03.410 --> 00:13:04.640
I don't want to make
you guys jealous--

00:13:04.640 --> 00:13:06.246
LESLIE TOBIN: --for those in
the UK who may not have access.

00:13:06.246 --> 00:13:07.610
BRIAN KELLY: For
the Brits out there.

00:13:07.610 --> 00:13:08.690
NICKY KELVIN: Hearing
this stuff is depressing.

00:13:08.690 --> 00:13:09.360
LESLIE TOBIN: [LAUGHS]

00:13:09.360 --> 00:13:10.280
BRIAN KELLY: So the
Sapphire Reserve

00:13:10.280 --> 00:13:13.250
is probably the top all around
travel credit card in the US.

00:13:13.250 --> 00:13:17.540
You earn triple points on
all travel and all dining.

00:13:17.540 --> 00:13:21.110
So travel is every cruise,
hotel, Uber, public transit,

00:13:21.110 --> 00:13:22.340
parking, tolls.

00:13:22.340 --> 00:13:24.170
It's ultra-- 3x.

00:13:24.170 --> 00:13:26.150
And the points are worth
1 and 1/2 cents each

00:13:26.150 --> 00:13:28.737
towards any travel you want.

00:13:28.737 --> 00:13:31.320
And then when you transfer them
to their partners like United,

00:13:31.320 --> 00:13:32.680
it just gets--

00:13:32.680 --> 00:13:34.610
it's so unbelievably lucrative.

00:13:34.610 --> 00:13:36.790
And for the first
four months, it

00:13:36.790 --> 00:13:39.650
was 100,000 points when
you got the card, plus you

00:13:39.650 --> 00:13:40.810
get 300 a year.

00:13:40.810 --> 00:13:44.630
It's a $450 a year card, but
it was the biggest no brainer.

00:13:44.630 --> 00:13:49.190
I think like a million people
got it in the first year.

00:13:49.190 --> 00:13:50.690
We were their launch partner.

00:13:50.690 --> 00:13:53.700
It now is like 60,000
or 50,000 points.

00:13:53.700 --> 00:13:55.940
But when you think
about earning 3x.

00:13:55.940 --> 00:13:58.420
I mean, in the US, it's not
just huge sign-up bonuses.

00:13:58.420 --> 00:14:00.170
Because the interchange
rate, here there's

00:14:00.170 --> 00:14:02.720
legislation that--
it's allegedly there

00:14:02.720 --> 00:14:04.190
to help consumers
that, you know,

00:14:04.190 --> 00:14:07.190
0.3% is what any
credit card company can

00:14:07.190 --> 00:14:11.510
charge to charge of merchant.

00:14:11.510 --> 00:14:13.410
In the US, it's like 3%.

00:14:13.410 --> 00:14:16.670
So why rewards are so rich
in the US is that merchants

00:14:16.670 --> 00:14:19.950
are paying 3% on everything,
so the credit card company,

00:14:19.950 --> 00:14:24.050
they make the 3% plus
annual fees plus interest.

00:14:24.050 --> 00:14:25.550
For people who spend
a lot of money,

00:14:25.550 --> 00:14:28.880
they'll give you rewards,
usually like 1% or 2% back.

00:14:28.880 --> 00:14:32.060
So here Amex is the
only one that it's 0.3%.

00:14:32.060 --> 00:14:34.330
They have a little bit
higher interchange,

00:14:34.330 --> 00:14:35.580
but it's still not that great.

00:14:35.580 --> 00:14:36.780
I mean 20,000 points.

00:14:36.780 --> 00:14:40.250
Nicky will get into
the exact cards.

00:14:40.250 --> 00:14:41.720
So it's a bonanza in the US.

00:14:41.720 --> 00:14:44.460
So if you ever get a chance to
get a social security number

00:14:44.460 --> 00:14:46.790
or work in the US for
like two months just

00:14:46.790 --> 00:14:48.530
to get a social security
number, because the credit cards

00:14:48.530 --> 00:14:48.980
are that good.

00:14:48.980 --> 00:14:49.700
LESLIE TOBIN: It's amazing.

00:14:49.700 --> 00:14:50.540
[LAUGHTER]

00:14:50.540 --> 00:14:51.550
NICKY KELVIN: This could
be the only reason--

00:14:51.550 --> 00:14:52.140
BRIAN KELLY: Is that
borderline unethical?

00:14:52.140 --> 00:14:52.760
[LAUGHTER]

00:14:52.760 --> 00:14:55.010
NICKY KELVIN: It's like where
I reveal the only reason

00:14:55.010 --> 00:14:57.140
I joined The Points Guy, like
I just want a social security

00:14:57.140 --> 00:14:59.000
number, start taking
out US credit cards.

00:14:59.000 --> 00:14:59.900
BRIAN KELLY: And also
at The Points Guy,

00:14:59.900 --> 00:15:02.120
one of our unique perks, is
we pay for all the credit card

00:15:02.120 --> 00:15:03.500
annual fees of our employees.

00:15:03.500 --> 00:15:05.150
I'm just very lucky that
none of my employers

00:15:05.150 --> 00:15:07.025
have been able to get
the Centurion card yet.

00:15:07.025 --> 00:15:07.667
[LAUGHTER]

00:15:07.667 --> 00:15:09.500
LESLIE TOBIN: So you've
established yourself

00:15:09.500 --> 00:15:11.833
as an expert in the US already,
and now you're obviously

00:15:11.833 --> 00:15:12.863
expanding into the UK.

00:15:12.863 --> 00:15:14.780
What have been some of
the biggest differences

00:15:14.780 --> 00:15:17.420
between the US market and
the UK market in terms

00:15:17.420 --> 00:15:18.565
of points in travel?

00:15:18.565 --> 00:15:19.940
BRIAN KELLY: I'll
let Nicky-- you

00:15:19.940 --> 00:15:21.770
want to speak to it, because
you've spent time in the US

00:15:21.770 --> 00:15:22.260
as well?

00:15:22.260 --> 00:15:24.110
NICKY KELVIN: Yeah, I mean, the
biggest thing is credit cards.

00:15:24.110 --> 00:15:24.818
LESLIE TOBIN: OK.

00:15:24.818 --> 00:15:28.680
NICKY KELVIN: So I think you
can have a strategy in the US

00:15:28.680 --> 00:15:30.440
that is heavily
credit card based,

00:15:30.440 --> 00:15:31.940
and it's pretty
much all you need

00:15:31.940 --> 00:15:34.950
to do very well out of
the miles and points game.

00:15:34.950 --> 00:15:37.470
I think you can earn
such huge amounts

00:15:37.470 --> 00:15:39.470
and be able to have the
really great experiences

00:15:39.470 --> 00:15:40.340
off the back of it.

00:15:40.340 --> 00:15:42.930
In the UK, you for sure
have to work harder.

00:15:42.930 --> 00:15:46.640
But that harder work is
sort of led to a feeling

00:15:46.640 --> 00:15:50.453
amongst the people in the UK
that there isn't even anything

00:15:50.453 --> 00:15:52.370
to be gained at all, and
that's the perception

00:15:52.370 --> 00:15:53.450
that we want to change.

00:15:53.450 --> 00:15:56.003
So the main difference
is credit cards

00:15:56.003 --> 00:15:57.920
and that if you want to
earn miles and points,

00:15:57.920 --> 00:15:59.370
you need to also look elsewhere.

00:15:59.370 --> 00:16:01.850
So credit cards are a start
and putting spend through

00:16:01.850 --> 00:16:04.700
on credit cards is
important in a solid way

00:16:04.700 --> 00:16:07.670
to accumulate points.

00:16:07.670 --> 00:16:10.820
But you also need to dip
into loads of other places.

00:16:10.820 --> 00:16:12.680
In the US, if you get
deep into the game,

00:16:12.680 --> 00:16:14.540
you can earn crazy,
crazy, crazy amounts.

00:16:14.540 --> 00:16:16.610
But even one credit card
sign-up bonus in the US

00:16:16.610 --> 00:16:19.410
is enough to really show
you something great.

00:16:19.410 --> 00:16:20.480
LESLIE TOBIN: OK, OK.

00:16:20.480 --> 00:16:21.300
Amazing.

00:16:21.300 --> 00:16:24.480
So I will admit, the first
few years of my career,

00:16:24.480 --> 00:16:25.880
I was traveling a ton for work.

00:16:25.880 --> 00:16:28.553
But I definitely did not take
advantage of points at all.

00:16:28.553 --> 00:16:29.720
I didn't have a credit card.

00:16:29.720 --> 00:16:31.750
I wasn't signed up for
any loyalty programs.

00:16:31.750 --> 00:16:32.130
BRIAN KELLY: [GASPS]

00:16:32.130 --> 00:16:33.005
LESLIE TOBIN: I know.

00:16:33.005 --> 00:16:33.590
It's horrible.

00:16:33.590 --> 00:16:36.710
So what would you advise
to other points newbies

00:16:36.710 --> 00:16:38.570
out there about kind
of getting started

00:16:38.570 --> 00:16:41.728
with travel and with points?

00:16:41.728 --> 00:16:43.020
BRIAN KELLY: You can do the UK.

00:16:43.020 --> 00:16:46.910
How many people here are
UK residents or citizens?

00:16:46.910 --> 00:16:48.175
Yeah, so it's a mostly UK.

00:16:48.175 --> 00:16:49.550
NICKY KELVIN: Does
anyone in here

00:16:49.550 --> 00:16:52.313
have or is able to take
out US credit cards?

00:16:52.313 --> 00:16:53.230
LESLIE TOBIN: [LAUGHS]

00:16:53.230 --> 00:16:54.628
NICKY KELVIN: Ooh, that's--

00:16:54.628 --> 00:16:55.670
BRIAN KELLY: Or married--

00:16:55.670 --> 00:16:57.560
I actually met a reader
at one of our events

00:16:57.560 --> 00:16:59.060
who said the happiest
day of my life

00:16:59.060 --> 00:17:01.130
was when I got married because
I could start taking credit

00:17:01.130 --> 00:17:02.260
cards out in my wife's name.

00:17:02.260 --> 00:17:02.760
[LAUGHTER]

00:17:02.760 --> 00:17:04.740
True story, in
front of his wife.

00:17:04.740 --> 00:17:06.319
He's like, I fly first class.

00:17:06.319 --> 00:17:08.490
I have no complaints.

00:17:08.490 --> 00:17:10.833
NICKY KELVIN: So in
the UK, the strategy--

00:17:10.833 --> 00:17:12.500
so we have a beginner's
guide, actually,

00:17:12.500 --> 00:17:15.530
on the site that gives
you these headline

00:17:15.530 --> 00:17:17.533
tips that you can start--

00:17:17.533 --> 00:17:18.950
these are the
things that you need

00:17:18.950 --> 00:17:20.130
to do to get going in the game.

00:17:20.130 --> 00:17:22.010
But the main things are
take out credit cards.

00:17:22.010 --> 00:17:24.020
There are various different
products in the UK--

00:17:24.020 --> 00:17:26.843
granted, not as good as the US,
and they've got slightly worse

00:17:26.843 --> 00:17:28.010
in the last couple of weeks.

00:17:28.010 --> 00:17:29.990
But there is still plenty to be.

00:17:29.990 --> 00:17:33.150
We've got some tears already
rolling in the audience.

00:17:33.150 --> 00:17:35.840
But for example, the Amex
Preferred Rewards Gold Card

00:17:35.840 --> 00:17:37.760
still offers 10,000
points as a sign-up

00:17:37.760 --> 00:17:39.270
with no annual fee for a year.

00:17:39.270 --> 00:17:41.990
So that's kind of 10,000
membership reward points,

00:17:41.990 --> 00:17:43.018
which are very flexible.

00:17:43.018 --> 00:17:44.810
You can transfer them
to different airlines

00:17:44.810 --> 00:17:45.710
to get you going.

00:17:45.710 --> 00:17:47.660
The British Airways
Premium Plus Card

00:17:47.660 --> 00:17:51.500
still offers 25,000 Avios
and the companion voucher

00:17:51.500 --> 00:17:54.488
which is a really
valuable benefit, which

00:17:54.488 --> 00:17:56.030
allows you to buy
one of yours ticket

00:17:56.030 --> 00:17:57.420
and get another one for free.

00:17:57.420 --> 00:17:59.720
So credit cards,
getting a credit card,

00:17:59.720 --> 00:18:02.990
is sort of step one, and then
conditioning yourself to use

00:18:02.990 --> 00:18:04.430
the credit card all the time.

00:18:04.430 --> 00:18:05.540
Just stop using cash.

00:18:05.540 --> 00:18:07.100
Stop using your debit card.

00:18:07.100 --> 00:18:10.880
We also say if you can't
pay off your bill in full

00:18:10.880 --> 00:18:12.557
on time every
month, credit cards

00:18:12.557 --> 00:18:13.890
are maybe not the thing for you.

00:18:13.890 --> 00:18:16.617
But if you can do that, just
put everything on your card,

00:18:16.617 --> 00:18:18.950
and earn a reward for every
single pound that you spend.

00:18:18.950 --> 00:18:19.640
LESLIE TOBIN: Yep.

00:18:19.640 --> 00:18:21.470
NICKY KELVIN: The other one,
which is really great is Tesco.

00:18:21.470 --> 00:18:23.920
A lot of people don't
realize that Tesco Club Card

00:18:23.920 --> 00:18:27.655
points convert into Avios
or Virgin Flying Club miles.

00:18:27.655 --> 00:18:29.030
So I worked out
that if you spend

00:18:29.030 --> 00:18:32.420
200 quid a week at Tesco, which
your average family probably

00:18:32.420 --> 00:18:36.980
does if you shop there across
shopping, petrol, online,

00:18:36.980 --> 00:18:40.040
after a year, you've enough
for 25,000 Avios, which

00:18:40.040 --> 00:18:42.170
is another big chunk.

00:18:42.170 --> 00:18:43.952
Shopping portals,
that's the next one.

