there's not that many
Marriott properties in the UK.

00:28:47.010 --> 00:28:49.010
I feel like the hotel
game isn't as strong here,

00:28:49.010 --> 00:28:51.140
but I think Marriott
is a decent--

00:28:51.140 --> 00:28:52.672
Hyatt's OK.

00:28:52.672 --> 00:28:54.880
I get a little less excited
about the hotel programs.

00:28:54.880 --> 00:28:55.505
What about you?

00:28:55.505 --> 00:28:58.110
NICKY KELVIN: Yeah, I mean,
hotel points are actually

00:28:58.110 --> 00:29:01.250
much harder to earn
here, because there's

00:29:01.250 --> 00:29:03.260
no lucrative credit
cards where you can

00:29:03.260 --> 00:29:04.430
be earning masses of points.

00:29:04.430 --> 00:29:06.680
And I think it's something
that's just a bit less sexy

00:29:06.680 --> 00:29:08.827
spoken about less.

00:29:08.827 --> 00:29:10.910
But actually, one thing
I'll add onto because I've

00:29:10.910 --> 00:29:12.200
used it a couple of times.

00:29:12.200 --> 00:29:15.620
With the Amex Platinum, you
get access to Amex fine hotels

00:29:15.620 --> 00:29:16.287
and resorts.

00:29:16.287 --> 00:29:18.620
And actually, they have some
incredible properties there

00:29:18.620 --> 00:29:20.000
with some amazing benefits.

00:29:20.000 --> 00:29:22.430
And just a couple of days
ago, I'm going to Indonesia.

00:29:22.430 --> 00:29:24.770
And I was looking
up Jakarta, and they

00:29:24.770 --> 00:29:26.860
have two hotels on
offer in Jakarta,

00:29:26.860 --> 00:29:30.450
a Mandarin Oriental and
I forget the other one.

00:29:30.450 --> 00:29:32.510
But the prices, it
wasn't that expensive.

00:29:32.510 --> 00:29:36.530
They were, for what
they were, maybe $260

00:29:36.530 --> 00:29:41.510
a night at these two hotels,
which were super luxury.

00:29:41.510 --> 00:29:44.040
The price on Booking.com,
Hotels.com, was about the same.

00:29:44.040 --> 00:29:45.290
It was maybe $10 less.

00:29:45.290 --> 00:29:49.250
But actually, you got $100 spa
or food and beverage credit

00:29:49.250 --> 00:29:50.900
for the stay, so
for a two-night stay

00:29:50.900 --> 00:29:52.760
that was a crazy
benefit, plus upgrade,

00:29:52.760 --> 00:29:55.993
plus 12:00 PM check-in,
plus 4:00 PM check out.

00:29:55.993 --> 00:29:57.160
All these different things--

00:29:57.160 --> 00:29:58.993
BRIAN KELLY: The
Gleneagles is a fine hotel,

00:29:58.993 --> 00:30:01.280
and they give two free
rounds of golf and free--

00:30:01.280 --> 00:30:05.690
it was like 400 pounds for
booking through Amex was

00:30:05.690 --> 00:30:06.420
the perk, which--

00:30:06.420 --> 00:30:06.860
LESLIE TOBIN:
That's a great deal.

00:30:06.860 --> 00:30:07.720
BRIAN KELLY: --of
course I didn't use.

00:30:07.720 --> 00:30:08.400
But--

00:30:08.400 --> 00:30:09.817
NICKY KELVIN: Yeah,
so that said--

00:30:09.817 --> 00:30:11.160
BRIAN KELLY: [INAUDIBLE]

00:30:11.160 --> 00:30:11.870
NICKY KELVIN:
--there are all sorts

00:30:11.870 --> 00:30:14.120
of ways you can extract
a little bit more value.

00:30:14.120 --> 00:30:18.080
I tend to use Hotels.com.

00:30:18.080 --> 00:30:20.030
Actually, on the
BA shopping portal,

00:30:20.030 --> 00:30:22.918
they have Avios earning
through those hotel programs.

00:30:22.918 --> 00:30:24.960
And actually, one other
thing that I really like,

00:30:24.960 --> 00:30:26.335
which people don't
talk about, is

00:30:26.335 --> 00:30:30.230
BA Holidays, where you can book
a flight and a hotel together.

00:30:30.230 --> 00:30:33.290
And they give you a discount
across the whole product.

00:30:33.290 --> 00:30:36.230
It also allows you to
just pay a deposit,

00:30:36.230 --> 00:30:37.740
and you pay 150 pounds.

00:30:37.740 --> 00:30:39.020
You pay close to the time.

00:30:39.020 --> 00:30:40.820
You get bonus Avios.

00:30:40.820 --> 00:30:44.388
And you see prices sometimes
really, really crazy prices,

00:30:44.388 --> 00:30:45.680
especially for European breaks.

00:30:45.680 --> 00:30:46.640
I often look at--

00:30:46.640 --> 00:30:50.390
you tick just five star,
in May, on a weekend,

00:30:50.390 --> 00:30:53.090
and it filters it all down,
European destinations.

00:30:53.090 --> 00:30:56.930
And you see things like
Budapest with flights

00:30:56.930 --> 00:31:02.882
on BA with two nights in a five
star hotel 139 pounds a person

00:31:02.882 --> 00:31:03.840
or something like that.

00:31:03.840 --> 00:31:05.600
So there's some really
amazing things on there.

00:31:05.600 --> 00:31:06.975
BRIAN KELLY: Which,
of course, we

00:31:06.975 --> 00:31:09.215
will write about and publish
at thepointsguy.co.uk.

00:31:09.215 --> 00:31:10.792
[LAUGHTER]

00:31:11.660 --> 00:31:13.730
By the way, we were
originally going to do

00:31:13.730 --> 00:31:17.950
the pointsguy.com/uk so we
could have all of our good SEO.

00:31:17.950 --> 00:31:20.510
For these darn
privacy laws, we had

00:31:20.510 --> 00:31:22.040
to start from
scratch on Thursday.

00:31:22.040 --> 00:31:24.530
So whoever here works in the
Google authority department

00:31:24.530 --> 00:31:26.238
in like the dark room
with the algorithm,

00:31:26.238 --> 00:31:29.180
if you could just pop us up
a couple notches, thank you.

00:31:29.180 --> 00:31:31.460
I hate to ask for favors, but--

00:31:31.460 --> 00:31:32.300
LESLIE TOBIN: I don't
think it works that way.

00:31:32.300 --> 00:31:33.300
BRIAN KELLY: No, I know.

00:31:33.300 --> 00:31:34.150
[LAUGHTER]

00:31:34.150 --> 00:31:35.680
That was the joke.

00:31:35.680 --> 00:31:37.650
But if not, if it does--

00:31:37.650 --> 00:31:38.275
you never know.

00:31:38.275 --> 00:31:40.233
LESLIE TOBIN: We're going
to take some audience

00:31:40.233 --> 00:31:42.790
questions, so if anybody wants
to line up at the microphone.

00:31:42.790 --> 00:31:45.250
And before we do that,
we'll talk a little bit

00:31:45.250 --> 00:31:46.330
about travel life.

00:31:46.330 --> 00:31:49.080
So you seem like you
are always on the road.

00:31:49.080 --> 00:31:52.000
You're hopping from one
plane ride to the next.

00:31:52.000 --> 00:31:54.670
How do you maintain
balance in your life?

00:31:54.670 --> 00:31:57.228
BRIAN KELLY: Well,
that's a great question.

00:31:57.228 --> 00:31:59.020
I think the biggest
thing like with jet lag

00:31:59.020 --> 00:32:00.322
is choosing the right flights.

00:32:00.322 --> 00:32:01.780
And you can choose
horrible flight.

00:32:01.780 --> 00:32:03.490
So when coming from
the US to London,

00:32:03.490 --> 00:32:06.783
I never, never, never
take the 4:00 or 5:00 PM.

00:32:06.783 --> 00:32:08.950
Who can sleep from 4:00 in
the afternoon to midnight

00:32:08.950 --> 00:32:10.325
and then be on a
normal schedule?

00:32:10.325 --> 00:32:14.128
So I like traveling
at 10:00 PM flight.

00:32:14.128 --> 00:32:15.670
It really makes a
difference in terms

00:32:15.670 --> 00:32:16.840
of just getting used to it.

00:32:16.840 --> 00:32:18.730
Also choosing the right plane--

00:32:18.730 --> 00:32:22.510
if you have a choice of a
clunky 30-year-old triple 7

00:32:22.510 --> 00:32:27.290
or the new BA or Virgin 787,
the 787 even in economy,

00:32:27.290 --> 00:32:28.620
it's better on your skin.

00:32:28.620 --> 00:32:29.912
It's a quieter plane.

00:32:29.912 --> 00:32:31.120
It's just a nicer experience.

00:32:31.120 --> 00:32:33.440
And those small things--

00:32:33.440 --> 00:32:35.950
I actually have been
using Dream Water, which

00:32:35.950 --> 00:32:39.100
is a melatonin little bottle.

00:32:39.100 --> 00:32:39.747
It's awesome.

00:32:39.747 --> 00:32:41.080
I try not to use too many like--

00:32:41.080 --> 00:32:42.940
I don't use like
Ambiens on planes.

00:32:42.940 --> 00:32:45.550
That's when you hear
the news article

00:32:45.550 --> 00:32:47.800
of people peeing in the
aisles, shouting obscenities.

00:32:47.800 --> 00:32:50.568
Usually that's people taking
hardcore sleeping pills

00:32:50.568 --> 00:32:51.610
that they're not used to.

00:32:51.610 --> 00:32:54.100
If you're going to, always
try them on the ground first.

00:32:54.100 --> 00:32:56.230
Don't mix them with alcohol.

00:32:56.230 --> 00:32:59.260
But then getting to a gym and
really just pushing yourself.

00:32:59.260 --> 00:33:01.170
Like in London, I actually
stay near Barry's.

00:33:01.170 --> 00:33:02.920
Because I know the
closer I am to the gym,

00:33:02.920 --> 00:33:03.970
the higher the odds are.

00:33:03.970 --> 00:33:08.660
So it's tough, but get lag
can truly ruin your life.

00:33:08.660 --> 00:33:11.350
So especially the New
York, London's really--

00:33:11.350 --> 00:33:13.240
I would much prefer to
be on a 12-hour flight

00:33:13.240 --> 00:33:14.488
than a six-hour flight.

00:33:14.488 --> 00:33:15.280
LESLIE TOBIN: Yeah.

00:33:15.280 --> 00:33:17.770
It's not quite long enough
to get a good night's sleep.

00:33:17.770 --> 00:33:19.320
What about for you?

00:33:19.320 --> 00:33:22.570
NICKY KELVIN: Actually, the
working out thing is really

00:33:22.570 --> 00:33:23.960
a big part of my strategy.

00:33:23.960 --> 00:33:25.740
I've kind of stopped drinking--

00:33:25.740 --> 00:33:28.120
not that I ever really
drank much, but just

00:33:28.120 --> 00:33:29.110
drinking plenty of--

00:33:29.110 --> 00:33:29.900
BRIAN KELLY: No,
let's be honest.

00:33:29.900 --> 00:33:30.880
It's really easy,
especially, when

00:33:30.880 --> 00:33:32.297
you redeem for
business and first,

00:33:32.297 --> 00:33:34.120
when it's like the
drinks are flowing.

00:33:34.120 --> 00:33:36.703
I mean, there's something about
having a wine buzz in the sky.

00:33:36.703 --> 00:33:39.340
But there's a very fine line
of like it's dehydrated.

00:33:39.340 --> 00:33:41.173
I mean, there's nothing
worse than waking up

00:33:41.173 --> 00:33:44.890
with like there's no ounce of
like hydration in your body,

00:33:44.890 --> 00:33:47.260
so yeah, trying to limit it.

00:33:47.260 --> 00:33:48.860
NICKY KELVIN: So
yeah, lots of water,

00:33:48.860 --> 00:33:52.960
and then working out when I
land, that always sorts me out,

00:33:52.960 --> 00:33:55.510
big sweat, blast
off the cobwebs,

00:33:55.510 --> 00:33:59.080
and sticking to local
time when I get home.

00:33:59.080 --> 00:34:01.060
Just forcing yourself
to stay awake

00:34:01.060 --> 00:34:03.270
and going to bed
at a normal time

00:34:03.270 --> 00:34:04.900
is just like the
most important thing.

00:34:04.900 --> 00:34:07.480
Because that dangerous
2:00 PM sleep

00:34:07.480 --> 00:34:09.790
when you wake up at
midnight and then can never

00:34:09.790 --> 00:34:12.097
sleep ever again, that's death.

00:34:12.097 --> 00:34:13.389
LESLIE TOBIN: Horrible feeling.

00:34:13.389 --> 00:34:15.250
BRIAN KELLY: And I
actually did cryotherapy

00:34:15.250 --> 00:34:16.250
my first time in London.

00:34:16.250 --> 00:34:17.792
So I have a new
YouTube series that's

00:34:17.792 --> 00:34:20.760
launching a week from
tomorrow, Being The Points Guy.

00:34:20.760 --> 00:34:22.510
It's like all my travels
around the world,

00:34:22.510 --> 00:34:24.093
and cool destinations,
and jumping out

00:34:24.093 --> 00:34:26.080
of helicopters, but
also the tactical stuff,

00:34:26.080 --> 00:34:28.570
like how I pack, how
to combat jet lag.

00:34:28.570 --> 00:34:30.100
And cryotherapy was amazing.

00:34:30.100 --> 00:34:32.937
And I also the other
day did an IV drip.

00:34:32.937 --> 00:34:34.270
It's really expensive in London.

00:34:34.270 --> 00:34:35.228
It was like 200 pounds.

00:34:35.228 --> 00:34:38.449
But an anesthesiologist
came to my hotel room,

00:34:38.449 --> 00:34:41.320
and they put in all
this amazing stuff.

00:34:41.320 --> 00:34:43.989
And it hydrates you.

00:34:43.989 --> 00:34:46.239
Like, they can do a
lot of witchcraft.

00:34:46.239 --> 00:34:49.873
And it was expensive, but if
you ever really need a reset--

00:34:49.873 --> 00:34:51.040
and I wasn't even hung over.

00:34:51.040 --> 00:34:52.300
Everyone's like, yeah right.

00:34:52.300 --> 00:34:55.060
NICKY KELVIN: Brian came in like
skipping into the pop-up shop.

00:34:55.060 --> 00:34:56.230
BRIAN KELLY: Like more
so than I am today,

00:34:56.230 --> 00:34:57.587
so if you can imagine that.

00:34:57.587 --> 00:34:58.483
Yeah.

00:34:58.483 --> 00:34:59.400
LESLIE TOBIN: Amazing.

00:34:59.400 --> 00:35:02.500
So I think we have
an audience question.

00:35:02.500 --> 00:35:03.430
AUDIENCE: Hello.

00:35:03.430 --> 00:35:04.150
I'm Sara.

00:35:04.150 --> 00:35:06.500
And my question to
you would be, which

00:35:06.500 --> 00:35:09.310
area do you think will be
prone to getting points

00:35:09.310 --> 00:35:10.060
in the future?

00:35:10.060 --> 00:35:11.890
I'm not sure if you've seen
"Black Mirror" where there's

00:35:11.890 --> 00:35:13.840
this episode where
people can get points

00:35:13.840 --> 00:35:17.440
through human interactions can
get either negative or positive

00:35:17.440 --> 00:35:18.280
points.

00:35:18.280 --> 00:35:19.822
So I was wondering,
what do you think

00:35:19.822 --> 00:35:23.380
would be the future
point rewarding systems?

00:35:23.380 --> 00:35:24.472
Any crazy ideas?

00:35:24.472 --> 00:35:25.930
BRIAN KELLY: The
future of loyalty?

00:35:29.030 --> 00:35:31.660
I mean, in the
US, loyalty points

00:35:31.660 --> 00:35:34.510
you can get for almost anything.

00:35:34.510 --> 00:35:39.410
But in terms of higher
points, I don't know.

00:35:39.410 --> 00:35:41.050
Do you have an answer to that?

00:35:41.050 --> 00:35:42.800
NICKY KELVIN: If I'm
talking about the UK,

00:35:42.800 --> 00:35:45.233
I'm hoping that the
UK public becomes

00:35:45.233 --> 00:35:47.150
more aware of miles and
points, and retailers,

00:35:47.150 --> 00:35:50.720
and other merchants start
to grow and expand programs.

00:35:50.720 --> 00:35:53.300
That would be great here, in
a way that they are already

00:35:53.300 --> 00:35:55.370
in the US.

00:35:55.370 --> 00:35:56.660
Just put more on offer.

00:35:56.660 --> 00:35:58.493
Actually, and there's
things that I find out

00:35:58.493 --> 00:36:01.070
about that I didn't know
that I hope roll out more.

00:36:01.070 --> 00:36:06.890
So for example, Waitrose, you
can put in your Amex card--

00:36:06.890 --> 00:36:09.890
any of your credit cards--
into the Flying Club shopping

00:36:09.890 --> 00:36:13.340
portal, and when you spend
in-store at Waitrose,

00:36:13.340 --> 00:36:14.923
they just pay you Virgin miles.

00:36:14.923 --> 00:36:17.090
I don't really understand
how that inspires loyalty.

00:36:17.090 --> 00:36:20.900
I guess it would make me spend
at Waitrose more in-store

00:36:20.900 --> 00:36:22.320
and pick that over
anywhere else.

00:36:22.320 --> 00:36:24.530
But if they rolled out
more of that kind of stuff,

00:36:24.530 --> 00:36:27.080
so hopefully that stuff works,
UK retailers and merchants

00:36:27.080 --> 00:36:31.400
become aware of this stuff and
realize it can drive loyalty.

00:36:31.400 --> 00:36:34.602
So more-- more of the same and
bigger of the same would be--

00:36:34.602 --> 00:36:36.560
I'm not saying that's
where I think it will go,

00:36:36.560 --> 00:36:37.070
but I hope it will.

00:36:37.070 --> 00:36:39.800
BRIAN KELLY: Using miles, it's
just a coupons, essentially--

00:36:39.800 --> 00:36:41.900
retailers, merchants, to
get people in a store.

00:36:41.900 --> 00:36:44.840
So people in the UK don't really
care that much about points,

00:36:44.840 --> 00:36:46.590
but we're already
talking to people.

00:36:46.590 --> 00:36:49.160
Like, once we get the
audience built up,

00:36:49.160 --> 00:36:51.290
we think we'll be able
to encourage more people

00:36:51.290 --> 00:36:53.510
to take a little
slice of your profit

00:36:53.510 --> 00:36:56.453
to give to people to get them
engaged and get new consumers.

00:36:56.453 --> 00:36:57.370
LESLIE TOBIN: Amazing.

00:36:57.370 --> 00:36:59.953
NICKY KELVIN: And actually just
on that point, the BA shopping

00:36:59.953 --> 00:37:01.880
portal, I was having
a conversation

00:37:01.880 --> 00:37:06.240
with the guy who's the product
manager for that whole system.

00:37:06.240 --> 00:37:10.070
And he said, we're in the
middle of launching new stuff

00:37:10.070 --> 00:37:12.950
to try really hard to get into
the minds of British people

00:37:12.950 --> 00:37:14.600
to shop through the portal more.

00:37:14.600 --> 00:37:17.480
So the people on the loyalty
side in the companies

00:37:17.480 --> 00:37:19.070
are aware, and they
are now starting

00:37:19.070 --> 00:37:22.282
to work harder to try and
do more and be attractive.

00:37:22.282 --> 00:37:23.115
LESLIE TOBIN: Great.

00:37:26.230 --> 00:37:27.760
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:37:27.760 --> 00:37:30.160
I have a much more specific
question than that.

00:37:30.160 --> 00:37:34.390
You sort of touched upon
it very briefly earlier.

00:37:34.390 --> 00:37:36.710
When traveling
with credit cards,

00:37:36.710 --> 00:37:39.410
there's typically-- so
for the Amex Gold Card,

00:37:39.410 --> 00:37:41.862
there's a 3% transaction fee.

00:37:41.862 --> 00:37:44.320
I was wondering what you guys
recommended in terms of like,

00:37:44.320 --> 00:37:46.240
should you take out
a second credit card

00:37:46.240 --> 00:37:50.210
for using abroad that has
no foreign transaction?

00:37:50.210 --> 00:37:52.120
And if so, which ones
would you recommend?

00:37:52.120 --> 00:37:53.770
NICKY KELVIN: I'll
tell you what I do,

00:37:53.770 --> 00:37:55.660
because I think this
is working really

00:37:55.660 --> 00:37:57.550
well for me at the moment.

00:37:57.550 --> 00:37:59.200
I have a Curve card.

00:37:59.200 --> 00:38:01.930
And Curve, I don't know how
many of you are aware of it,

00:38:01.930 --> 00:38:04.530
but you can have all of your
credit cards and debit cards

00:38:04.530 --> 00:38:05.570
sitting behind it.

00:38:05.570 --> 00:38:07.430
And you can sort of
select which one.

00:38:07.430 --> 00:38:08.830
It's actually quite cool.

00:38:08.830 --> 00:38:09.790
You pick the card.

00:38:09.790 --> 00:38:11.582
When you pay with your
curve, it charges it

00:38:11.582 --> 00:38:13.240
to one of your credit cards.

00:38:13.240 --> 00:38:15.610
And you have 14 days
to change which one.

00:38:15.610 --> 00:38:17.740
So it's called the Go
Back in Time function.

00:38:17.740 --> 00:38:19.300
And seven days later, you
can be like, actually,

00:38:19.300 --> 00:38:20.967
I'm not going to
charge it to that card.

00:38:20.967 --> 00:38:22.340
I'm going to charge this card.

00:38:22.340 --> 00:38:25.420
Now, they just launched Amex
functionality again on that,

00:38:25.420 --> 00:38:26.350
and it's such a shame.

00:38:26.350 --> 00:38:28.350
Because they give you a
MasterCard, and it means

00:38:28.350 --> 00:38:32.560
you can spend your Amex anywhere
and spend abroad with no fees

00:38:32.560 --> 00:38:36.520
because it charges
as a purchase.

00:38:36.520 --> 00:38:38.410
You can even take out
of a cash machine,

00:38:38.410 --> 00:38:39.830
and you don't pay
interest on it.

00:38:39.830 --> 00:38:41.622
There are some limits
on the amount of cash

00:38:41.622 --> 00:38:43.822
